## Usage Examples

### Remote app session

*ASP.NET Core*
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSystemWebAdapters()
    .AddJsonSessionSerializer(options => ClassLibrary.SessionUtils.RegisterSessionKeys(options.KnownKeys))
    .AddRemoteAppSession(options =>
    {
        options.RemoteApp = new(builder.Configuration["ReverseProxy:Clusters:fallbackCluster:Destinations:fallbackApp:Address"]);
        options.ApiKey = ClassLibrary.SessionUtils.ApiKey;
    });
```

*ASP.NET Framework*
```csharp
  Application.AddSystemWebAdapters()
                .AddRemoteAppSession(
                    options => options.ApiKey = ClassLibrary.SessionUtils.ApiKey,
                    options => ClassLibrary.SessionUtils.RegisterSessionKeys(options.KnownKeys));
```

## Wrapping `Microsoft.AspNetCore.ISession`

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSystemWebAdapters()
    .AddJsonSessionSerializer(options => ClassLibrary.SessionUtils.RegisterSessionKeys(options.KnownKeys))
    .WrapAspNetCoreSession();
```

## Alternative Designs

- Currently, the design is a bit more difficult on ASP.NET Framework to allow for full customization of things like serialization due to no in-built DI. In order to support customizations, we need a lot more extension methods on ASP.NET Framework

## Background and Motivation

We've been developing some [adapters](https://github.com/dotnet/systemweb-adapters) to help with migrating from ASP.NET Framework that adapter the `System.Web.HttpContext` to the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.HttpContext`. We've released Preview 1 and would like to review the API shape.

This issue focuses on the APIs that will be used on the ASP.NET Core/ASP.NET Framework applications to add functionality in.

Related API Designs:

- #42090
- #42092

