## Usage Examples

### ASP.NET Core

On ASP.NET Core, the configuration is done with services and middleware:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSystemWebAdapters()
    .AddJsonSessionSerializer(options => ClassLibrary.SessionUtils.RegisterSessionKeys(options.KnownKeys))
    .AddRemoteAppSession(options =>
    {
        options.RemoteApp = new(builder.Configuration["ReverseProxy:Clusters:fallbackCluster:Destinations:fallbackApp:Address"]);
        options.ApiKey = ClassLibrary.SessionUtils.ApiKey;
    });

  ...

  app.UseSystemWebAdapters();
```

Some behavior requires middleware that will add cost to the request/response and thus are opted-into. These follow a pattern that a specific metadata must be added to the endpoint to enable it. An example is session, that will be loaded for endpoints that needed it. 

In order to use it on all endpoints, there's a helper method:

```
app.MapDefaultControllerRoute()
  .RequireSystemWebAdapterSession();
```

This can also be opted-into at a controller/route level:

```csharp
[Microsoft.AspNetCore.SystemWebAdapters.Session]
public class SomeController : ApiController
{

}
```

### ASP.NET Framework

On ASP.NET Framework, we insert a single module (SystemWebAdaptersModule) that then will load additional modules if required. This is done in a fluent syntax that tries to mimic the setup of ASP.NET Core. However, because `IServiceCollection` isn't available on framework, we have the `ISystemWebAdapterBuilder` be a collection of `IHttpModule` instances that could be added:

```csharp
using System.Web.Http;
using System.Web.Mvc;
using System.Web.Optimization;
using System.Web.Routing;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.SystemWebAdapters;

namespace MvcApp
{
    public class MvcApplication : System.Web.HttpApplication
    {
        protected void Application_Start()
        {
            AreaRegistration.RegisterAllAreas();
            GlobalConfiguration.Configure(WebApiConfig.Register);
            FilterConfig.RegisterGlobalFilters(GlobalFilters.Filters);
            RouteConfig.RegisterRoutes(RouteTable.Routes);
            BundleConfig.RegisterBundles(BundleTable.Bundles);

            Application.AddSystemWebAdapters()
                .AddProxySupport(options => options.UseForwardedHeaders = true)
                .AddRemoteAppSession(
                    options => options.ApiKey = ClassLibrary.SessionUtils.ApiKey,
                    options => ClassLibrary.SessionUtils.RegisterSessionKeys(options.KnownKeys));
        }
    }
}
```

## Alternative Designs

- An alternative design to bring the declaration on .NET Framework more in line (and align the types a bit better) would be to add the `Microsoft.Extensions` packages. The minimum set would be `Microsoft.Extensions.Options` and `Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection`. That way services on the framework side could be overridden in the same way as core. So far, we've been hesitant to bring in new packages with this level (the adapters currently don't have any new dependencies it adds to a framework app)

## Background and Motivation

We've been developing some [adapters](https://github.com/dotnet/systemweb-adapters) to help with migrating from ASP.NET Framework that adapter the `System.Web.HttpContext` to the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.HttpContext`. We've released Preview 1 and would like to review the API shape.

This issue focuses on the APIs being brought forth from `System.Web`. The package targets .NET Standard, .NET 6, and .NET Framework. On .NET Framework, the types unify with `System.Web.dll`. Subsequent issues will have the APIs for the .NET Core/.NET Framework APIs needed to tie things together.

Related API Designs:

- #42091
- #42092

